Primary ciliary dyskinesia 21, also precisely known as CILD21 or primary ciliary dyskinesia 21 without situs inversus, is a subtype of primary ciliary dyskinesia. It is defined by its autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, characterized by a missing Nexin link, infantile onset of chronic sinopulmonary infections, and is caused by a homozygous mutation in the DRC1 gene located on chromosome 2p23.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 22 (PCD22) is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with defects in both the outer and inner dynein arms, leading to recurrent respiratory infections, persistent rhinosinusitis, otitis media, and chronic cough. Additionally, the presence of situs abnormalities can vary. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ZMYND10 gene located on chromosome 3p21. Notably, primary ciliary dyskinesia 22 is also known by its exact synonyms CILD22 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 22 with or without situs inversus. Among its symptoms, chronic cough is a significant feature.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 14 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance featuring an inner dynein arm defect and axonemal disorganization, leading to chronic upper and lower airway infections. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CCDC39 gene located on chromosome 3q26. It is exactly synonymized with CILD14 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 14 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 3 is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with an outer dynein arm defect, ciliary akinesia, and a variable occurrence of situs inversus. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DNAH5 gene located on chromosome 5p15. Additionally, Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 3 is exactly synonymous with CILD3 and "Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 3 with or without situs inversus".

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 29 is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, oligocilia, and early childhood onset of recurrent respiratory infections. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CCNO gene on chromosome 5p15. It is also exactly synonymous with CILD29 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 29 without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 12 (PCD12), also known exactly as CILD12 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 12 without situs inversus, is a specific type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia. It is characterized by several symptoms including chronic and wet coughs, along with a disease feature of bronchiectasis. The definition of PCD12 highlights its manifestation through reduced exercise tolerance, chronic wet cough, recurrent respiratory infections, bronchiectasis, and nasal symptoms. The condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the RSPH9 gene located on chromosome 6p21.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 11 (PCD11) is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia. It is characterized by several symptoms and features, including underweight, chronic cough, wet cough, and bronchiectasis. The definition of PCD11 encompasses a condition that leads to reduced exercise tolerance, chronic wet cough, recurrent respiratory infections, bronchiectasis, nasal symptoms, ear obstruction with consequent hearing problems, low weight, and short stature. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RSPH4A gene located on chromosome 6q22. PCD11 is also precisely known by two synonyms: CILD11 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 11 without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 32, which is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia, is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with a near absence of radial spokes, respiratory distress in term neonates, impaired mucociliary clearance, chronic respiratory infections, bronchiectasis, and infertility. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RSPH3 gene located on chromosome 6q25. Additionally, Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 32 is exactly synonymous with CILD32 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 32 without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 18 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with outer and inner dynein arm defect. It manifests early in infantile onset with recurrent sinopulmonary infections, male infertility, and the occurrence of situs inversus varies. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the HEATR2 gene on chromosome 7p22. It is also exactly known as CILD18 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 18 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 7 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. It is associated with chronic respiratory infections, chronic sinusitis, recurrent bronchitis, and pneumonia, which begin in infancy or early childhood. This condition's material basis is a mutation in the DNAH11 gene located on chromosome 7p21. Moreover, primary ciliary dyskinesia 7 is exactly synonymous with CILD7 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 7 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 6 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia and is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by partial outer dynein arm defect. It has a material basis in mutation in the TXNDC3 gene located on chromosome 7p14.1. Additionally, primary ciliary dyskinesia 6 is exactly synonymous with CILD6.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 28 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia that is specifically characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with defects in both the outer and inner dynein arms, leading to recurrent upper and lower airway disease, bronchiectasis, and decreased fertility. This condition has its material basis in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SPAG1 gene located on chromosome 8q22. Additionally, primary ciliary dyskinesia 28 is exactly synonymous with CILD28 and also known as primary ciliary dyskinesia 28 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 19 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with outer and inner dynein arm defect, chronic sinopulmonary infections, asthenospermia, and immotile cilia. This condition is defined by a homozygous mutation in the LRRC6 gene on chromosome 8q24. It is exactly synonymous with CILD19 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 19 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 23 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia. It is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with an outer dynein arm defect, respiratory distress, and recurrent upper and lower airway infections. This condition has a variable occurrence of situs inversus and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ARMC4 gene on chromosome 10p. Furthermore, primary ciliary dyskinesia 23 is precisely referred to by two exact synonyms: CILD23 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 23 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 34 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, with symptoms including childhood onset of recurrent sinopulmonary infections and male infertility. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the DNAJB13 gene located on chromosome 11q13. It is also exactly synonymous with CILD34 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 34 without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 27 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with neonatal respiratory distress, recurrent upper and lower airway disease, and bronchiectasis. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CCDC65 gene on chromosome 12q13. It is also exactly synonymous with CILD27 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 27 without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 10 is a subtype of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by the absence of outer and inner dynein arms, chronic otitis media, sinusitis, recurrent pneumonia, and it variably occurs with situs inversus. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the KTU gene located on chromosome 14q21. It is exactly synonymous with CILD10 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 10 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 16 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with the absence of ciliary outer dynein arms, early infantile onset of respiratory distress, and a variable occurrence of situs inversus. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the DNAL1 gene located on chromosome 14q24.3. It is also exactly synonymous with CILD16 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 16 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 4 is a specific type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia. It is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by a partial absence of the inner dynein arms with variable occurrence of situs inversus, and it has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 15q13.1-q15.1. This condition is also exactly synonymous with CILD4 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 4 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 25 (CILD25), also known as Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 25 with or without situs inversus, is a specific type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia. It is defined as a Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with inner and outer dynein arm defect, recurrent upper and lower airway disease, bronchiectasis, decreased fertility, and the variable occurrence of laterality defects. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DYX1C1 gene located on chromosome 15q21.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 8 is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia, which is defined as a primary ciliary dyskinesia that has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 15q24-q25. It has exact synonyms including CILD8 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 8 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 5 is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia that is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with early onset of a progressive decline in lung function, and it has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the HYDIN gene on chromosome 16q22. It also has exact synonyms, including CILD5 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 5 without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 13 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by inner and outer dynein arm defects, immotile cilia, and the variable occurrence of laterality defects. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LRRC50 gene on chromosome 16q23-q24. This condition is also exactly synonymous with CILD13 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 13 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 33 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections, and has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the GAS8 gene on chromosome 16q24. It is exactly synonymous with CILD33 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 33 without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 35 is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with absent outer dynein arms, immotile cilia, variable occurrence of laterality defects, and recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TTC25 gene on chromosome 17q21. It is exactly synonymous with CILD35 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 35 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 17 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with inner and outer dynein arm defects. It typically presents with early infantile onset of respiratory distress and may variably present with laterality defects. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the CCDC103 gene located on chromosome 17q21. Additionally, primary ciliary dyskinesia 17 is exactly synonymous with CILD17 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 17 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 9 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia that is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with an outer dynein arm defect, neonatal respiratory distress, sinusitis, otitis, bronchiectasis, and a variable occurrence of laterality defects. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the DNAI2 gene on chromosome 17q25. It is also known by its exact synonyms, CILD9 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 9 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 15 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with inner dynein arm defect, axonemal disorganization, and recurrent respiratory infections. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CCDC40 gene located on chromosome 17q25. It is also known by its exact synonyms, CILD15 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 15 with or without situs inversus.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 30 is a specific type of primary ciliary dyskinesia, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with an outer dynein arm defect. This condition leads to recurrent upper and lower airway disease, bronchiectasis, nasal blockages, polyps, otitis media, and a variable occurrence of laterality defects. The condition's material basis is found in a homozygous mutation in the CCDC151 gene on chromosome 19p13. Primary ciliary dyskinesia 30 is exactly synonymous with CILD30 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 30 without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 20 is a type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia, characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with an outer dynein arm defect. It typically begins in infancy with chronic sinopulmonary infections and may include variable occurrences of laterality defects. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CCDC114 gene on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 20 is exactly synonymous with CILD20 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 20 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 2 (PCD2) is a specific type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with defects in both the inner and outer dynein arms, resulting in symptoms such as otitis media, sinusitis, chronic cough, and recurrent respiratory infections. Furthermore, it may variably present with laterality defects. The condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the DNAAF3 gene located on chromosome 19q13. PCD2 is also known by its exact synonyms, CILD2 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 2 with or without situs inversus, indicating that it is a condition that encompasses cases with or without situs inversus as part of its clinical presentation.

Primary ciliary dyskinesia 26 is a type of primary ciliary dyskinesia, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with inner and outer dynein arm defect, neonatal respiratory distress, recurrent upper and lower airway disease, bronchiectasis, and variable occurrence of laterality defects. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the C21ORF59 gene on chromosome 21q22. It is exactly synonymous with CILD26 and primary ciliary dyskinesia 26 with or without situs inversus.

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 24 is a specific type of Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia. It is defined as a Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, manifesting with sinopulmonary infection and subfertility. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RSPH1 gene located on chromosome 21q22. Additionally, Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 24 is exactly synonymous with CILD24 and Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia 24 without situs inversus.

Wolfram Syndrome 1 is a specific type of Wolfram Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a group of conditions including diabetes mellitus, optic atrophy, deafness, and potentially other disorders. This disease has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WFS1 gene located on chromosome 4p16.1. Wolfram Syndrome 1 is distinct and separate from Wolfram Syndrome 2. Additionally, Wolfram Syndrome 1 is also known by its exact synonyms: DIDMOAD, WFS1, and diabetes mellitus AND insipidus with optic atrophy AND deafness, indicating its diverse yet specific symptomatology.

Wolfram Syndrome 2, also known exactly as WFS2, is a type of Wolfram Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by its autosomal recessive inheritance, which at least involves a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, and exhibits symptoms including bleeding. This neurodegenerative disorder is defined by a combination of diabetes mellitus, high frequency sensorineural hearing loss, optic atrophy or neuropathy, and defective platelet aggregation that leads to peptic ulcer bleeding. The condition's material basis lies in the autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CISD2 gene on chromosome 4q24.

Megaconial type congenital muscular dystrophy is a form of congenital muscular dystrophy and is also classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is associated with conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and diseases that have their basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of early-onset muscle wasting and intellectual disability. It features enlarged mitochondria that are more prevalent towards the periphery of the fibers, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CHKB gene on chromosome 22q13. Megaconial type congenital muscular dystrophy is also known by several exact synonyms, including congenital megaconial myopathy, congenital muscular dystrophy due to phosphatidylcholine biosynthesis defect, congenital muscular dystrophy with mitochondrial structural abnormalities, and megaconial congenital muscular dystrophy.

Rigid spine muscular dystrophy 1 is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy, autosomal recessive disease, spinal disease, and it at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, it at least has symptoms of muscle weakness and the disease has its location in the vertebral column. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by intrasarcoplasmic aggregates of desmin resulting in spinal rigidity, abnormal posture (limitation of neck and trunk flexure), progressive scoliosis of the spine, early marked cervico-axial muscle weakness with relatively preserved strength and function of the extremities, and progressive respiratory insufficiency, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SEPN1 gene on chromosome 1p36. Rigid spine muscular dystrophy 1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including Eichsfeld type congenital muscular dystrophy, MDRS1, RSMD1, RSS, SEPN1-related myopathy, classic MmD, classic multiminicore disease, classic multiminicore myopathy, congenital merosin-positive muscular dystrophy with early spine rigidity, desmin-related myopathy with Mallory bodies, desmin-related myopathy with Mallory body-like inclusions, early-onset desmin-related myopathy, rigid spine syndrome, severe classic form minicore myopathy, severe classic form multicore myopathy, and severe classic form multiminicore disease.

Congenital muscular dystrophy 1b (CMD1B), also known exactly as MDC1B and congenital muscular dystrophy type 1B, is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy and an autosomal recessive disease. It emerges from autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness. Furthermore, this condition is attributed to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CMD1B is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy marked by autosomal recessive inheritance of proximal muscle weakness, muscle hypertrophy, and early respiratory failure, which is caused by a variation in the chromosome region 1q42.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b5 is categorized as a subtype of autosomal recessive disease and muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b. It is described as a congenital muscular dystrophy, which is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with variable penetrance of intellectual disability and structural brain abnormalities. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FKRP gene on chromosome 19q13.3. Furthermore, muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type b5 is also known by several exact synonyms: FKRP-related congenital muscular dystrophy, MDC1C, MDDGB5, congenital muscular dystrophy 1C, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (congenital with or without impaired intellectual development or mental retardation), type B, 5.

Congenital Merosin Deficient Muscular Dystrophy 1A is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy and also a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with symptoms such as muscle weakness. Additionally, the disease has its basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. A detailed definition describes it as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of muscle weakness that is apparent at birth or in the first 6 months of life, along with frequent development of periventricular white matter abnormalities. This condition is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LAMA2 gene on chromosome 6q22. Moreover, Congenital Merosin Deficient Muscular Dystrophy 1A is precisely synonymous with CMD1A, MDC1A, Merosin-negative congenital muscular dystrophy, and congenital muscular dystrophy due to laminin alpha2 deficiency.

Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B6 is a specific form of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the broader category of muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B. It is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance involving muscular dystrophy with mental retardation and structural brain abnormalities. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LARGE gene located on chromosome 22q12. Muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy type B6 is also known by several exact synonyms, including MDC1D, MDDGB6, congenital muscular dystrophy LARGE-related, congenital muscular dystrophy type 1D, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (congenital with impaired intellectual development), type B, 6. Another synonym is muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (congenital with mental retardation), type B, 6, indicating its association with certain autosomal recessive inheritance patterns.

Congenital muscular dystrophy due to integrin alpha 7 deficiency is a specific type of congenital muscular dystrophy and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by having its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This condition is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy with autosomal recessive inheritance that results from compound heterozygous mutation in the ITGA7 gene on chromosome 12q13. It is also known by exact synonyms such as congenital muscular dystrophy with ITGA7 deficiency, congenital muscular dystrophy with integrin alpha-7 deficiency, and congenital myopathy due to integrin alpha-7 deficiency.

Congenital muscular dystrophy due to LMNA mutation is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy and also falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, it is defined as a congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LMNA gene located on chromosome 1q22. Furthermore, congenital muscular dystrophy due to LMNA mutation is exactly synonymous with L-CMD, LMNA-related congenital muscular dystrophy, and congenital muscular dystrophy LMNA-related.

Long QT Syndrome 1 is a type of Long QT Syndrome, autosomal dominant disease, and digenic disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in both autosomal dominant inheritance and digenic inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a long QT syndrome that arises from dominant inheritance of a mutation in the KCNQ1 gene located on chromosome 11p15.5-p15.4. Additionally, it has the exact synonyms LQT1 and ventricular fibrillation with prolonged QT interval.

Long QT syndrome 2 (LQT2) is a type of autosomal dominant and digenic disease, and it is a specific form of long QT syndrome. It is characterized by at least having a material basis in some autosomal dominant and digenic inheritances. Specifically, Long QT syndrome 2 is defined as a long QT syndrome that results from the dominant inheritance of a mutation in the KCNH2 gene located on chromosome 7q36.1.

Long QT syndrome 3 is a type of Long QT syndrome, autosomal dominant disease, and digenic disease. It is characterized by having its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and digenic inheritance. Specifically, Long QT syndrome 3, also known exactly as LQT3, is defined by a dominant inheritance of a mutation in the SCN5A gene located on chromosome 3p22.2.

Long QT syndrome 5 is a type of autosomal dominant and digenic disease, as well as a type of Long QT syndrome, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant and digenic inheritance. It is defined as a Long QT syndrome that has a material basis in dominant inheritance of a mutation in the KCNE1 gene on chromosome 21q22.12. Furthermore, Long QT syndrome 5 has the exact synonym LQT5.

Long QT syndrome 6 is a type of Long QT syndrome, characterized as an autosomal dominant and digenic disease. It is specifically defined by a long QT interval syndrome that has its material basis in the dominant inheritance of a mutation in the KCNE2 gene located on chromosome 21q22.11. Furthermore, it is associated with types that have at least a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and some digenic inheritance. Long QT syndrome 6 is also exactly synonymous with LQT6.

Long QT syndrome 8 is a subtype of Long QT syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by a prolonged QT interval and polymorphic ventricular tachycardia (torsades de pointes). This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1C gene located on chromosome 12p13.33. Long QT syndrome 8 is exactly synonymous with LQT8 and has an exact match with OMIM:618447.

Long QT Syndrome 9 is a type of Long QT Syndrome, which is characterized as an autosomal dominant and digenic disease. This condition also has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and digenic inheritance. It is defined by a long QT syndrome that arises from a mutation of the CAV3 gene on chromosome 3p25.3. Additionally, Long QT Syndrome 9 is exactly synonymous with LQT9.

Long QT Syndrome 10 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of Long QT Syndrome, characterized specifically by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Long QT Syndrome that has its material basis in the dominant inheritance of a mutation in the SCN4B gene located on chromosome 11q23.3. Additionally, Long QT Syndrome 10 is exactly synonymous with LQT10.

Long QT syndrome 11 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of long QT syndrome characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a long QT syndrome that results from a dominant inheritance of a mutation in the AKAP9 gene located on chromosome 7q21.2. Furthermore, Long QT syndrome 11 is exactly synonymous with LQT11.

Long QT Syndrome 12 (LQT12) is a type of Long QT Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, Long QT Syndrome 12 is defined by a dominant inheritance of a mutation in the SNTA1 gene located on chromosome 20q11.21.

Long QT syndrome 13 is a type of Long QT syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Long QT syndrome that has its material basis in the dominant inheritance of a mutation in the KCNJ5 gene on chromosome 11q24.3. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with LQT13.

Long QT syndrome 14 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Long QT syndrome, characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined by the dominant inheritance of a mutation in the CALM1 gene located on chromosome 14q32.11. Additionally, Long QT syndrome 14 is exactly synonymous with LQT14.

Long QT syndrome 15 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of long QT syndrome that is fundamentally caused by an autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined by the dominant inheritance of a mutation in the CALM2 gene located on chromosome 2p21. Additionally, Long QT syndrome 15 is exactly synonymous with LQT15.

Congenital Myasthenic Syndrome 8 (CMS8) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of congenital myasthenic syndrome. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, presenting symptoms such as muscle weakness, and having its disease basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, CMS8 is defined as a congenital myasthenic syndrome characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of prominent defects of both the pre- and postsynaptic regions and muscle weakness. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AGRN gene on chromosome 1p. CMS8 is also exactly synonymous with "congenital myasthenic syndrome 8 with pre- and postsynaptic defects" and "congenital myasthenic syndrome due to agrin deficiency."

Congenital Myasthenic Syndrome 15 (CMS15) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which belongs to the broader category of congenital myasthenic syndromes. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is attributed to some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CMS15 is specifically associated with muscle weakness as a symptom. The disease is defined as a congenital myasthenic syndrome that is characterized by the onset of progressive fatigable proximal muscle weakness in childhood and has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the ALG14 gene on chromosome 1p21. CMS15 is also known by its exact synonyms, including "CMS15" and "congenital myasthenic syndrome 15 without tubular aggregates."

Congenital Myasthenic Syndrome 7 (CMS7) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of congenital myasthenic syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by the autosomal dominant inheritance of presynaptic defects, with the onset of symptoms occurring in early childhood. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SYT2 gene on chromosome 1q32. Moreover, CMS7 is also referred to by its exact synonyms, including "CMS7" and "congenital myasthenic syndrome 7 presynaptic." This condition is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth, indicating its origins in genetic abnormalities that affect individuals from early stages of development.

Congenital Myasthenic Syndrome 12 (CMS12), also precisely known as congenital myasthenia 12 with tubular aggregates, is a specific type of congenital myasthenic syndrome. It is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease, indicating that it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Moreover, CMS12 is characterized by having symptoms that include muscle weakness and is based on abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The definition of CMS12 highlights that it is a congenital myasthenic syndrome distinguished by autosomal recessive inheritance, where the onset of proximal muscle weakness occurs in the first decade and generally responds well to acetylcholinesterase inhibitor treatment. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GFPT1 gene on chromosome 2p13.

Congenital Myasthenic Syndrome 20 (CMS20) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of congenital myasthenic syndrome. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CMS20 is defined as a congenital myasthenic syndrome characterized by severe hypotonia associated with episodic apnea, which is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC5A7 gene on chromosome 2q12. Moreover, CMS20 has exact synonyms "CMS20" and "congenital myasthenic syndrome 20 presynaptic."

Congenital Myasthenic Syndrome 1B (CMS1B) is a type of congenital myasthenic syndrome, which is characterized as both an autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive disease. It has a material basis in some autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance. CMS1B exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. Additionally, the disease has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CMS1B is defined as a congenital myasthenic syndrome characterized by defects in postsynaptic neuromuscular junctions with early-onset progressive muscle weakness, which has its material basis in a mutation in the CHRNA1 gene on chromosome 2q. Furthermore, CMS1B is also known by the exact synonyms CMS1B and congenital myasthenic syndrome 1B, fast-channel.

Congenital myasthenic syndrome 1a is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of congenital myasthenic syndrome. It is defined by predominantly autosomal dominant inheritance of defects in postsynaptic neuromuscular junctions, characterized by early-onset progressive muscle weakness. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the CHRNA1 gene on chromosome 2q, and it is associated with symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. Furthermore, congenital myasthenic syndrome 1a is linked to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is also known by exact synonyms CMS IIa, CMS1A, congenital myasthenic syndrome 1A, slow-channel, and congenital myasthenic syndrome type IIa.

Congenital myasthenic syndrome 3c is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also a specific type of congenital myasthenic syndrome. This condition is characterized by being associated with autosomal recessive inheritance and has symptoms including muscle weakness. It is related to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. Congenital myasthenic syndrome 3c is defined as a congenital myasthenic syndrome that is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of postsynaptic neuromuscular junction defects, low amplitude of the miniature endplate potential and current, and early-onset muscle weakness. This condition has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the CHRND gene on chromosome 2q37. Moreover, congenital myasthenic syndrome 3c has an exact synonym: congenital myasthenic syndrome 3C associated with acetylcholine receptor deficiency.

Congenital myasthenic syndrome 3b (CMS3B), also known exactly as CMS3B and congenital myasthenic syndrome 3B, fast-channel, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of congenital myasthenic syndrome. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of postsynaptic neuromuscular junction defects, which result in a rapid decay in endplate current and a failure to reach the threshold for depolarization, alongside early onset progressive muscular weakness. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CHRND gene on chromosome 2q37. Hereditary spastic paraplegia 5A (HSP 5A) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by progressive muscle weakness and paraplegia, which stems from a mutation in the CYP7B1 gene on chromosome 8q12. This condition not only has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance but also exhibits symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. HSP 5A is also known by its exact synonyms: SPG5A, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 5A, and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 5A.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 6 (HSP6) is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is associated with autosomal dominant inheritance due to its material basis. HSP6 is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that is typically characterized by a rapidly progressive and severe form of the condition. This progression is attributed to a mutation in the NIPA1 gene located on chromosome 15q11.2. Furthermore, HSP6 is also known by several exact synonyms, including FSP3, SPG6, autosomal dominant familial spastic paraplegia type 3, autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 6, and autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia type 6.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 61 (SPG61) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition results from a mutation in the ARL6IP1 gene located on chromosome 16p12. SPG61 is also known by its exact synonyms: autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 61 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 61.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 62 (HSP62) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia, which is an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. HSP62 is defined by a mutation in the ERLIN1 gene on chromosome 10q24. It is precisely known by its synonyms: SPG62, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 62, and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 62.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 63 (HSP63) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific type of inheritance that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined by a mutation in the AMPD2 gene located on chromosome 1p13. HSP63 is also known by its exact synonyms: SPG63, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 63, and spastic paraplegia 63.

Hereditary Spastic Paraplegia 64 (HSP64) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. Its characteristics stem from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, HSP64 is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that results from a mutation in the ENTPD1 gene located on chromosome 10q24. It is also precisely known by the synonyms SPG64, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 64, and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 64.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 7, which is also exactly known as SPG7, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 7, and spastic paraplegia type 7, is a kind of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease. It falls into the category of diseases that at least have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by a slowly progressive onset that usually occurs between the ages of 18 and 60 years. It is generally associated with more severe spasticity and has its material basis in mutations in the SPG7 gene located on chromosome 16q24.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 72a (HSP72a) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and can be described as both an autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive inheritance patterns. Specifically, HSP72a is defined by a hereditary spastic paraplegia that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the REEP2 gene located on chromosome 5q31.2. Furthermore, hereditary spastic paraplegia 72a is also known by its exact synonyms, SPG72 and autosomal spastic paraplegia type 72.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 73, which is also precisely known as SPG73, autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 73, and autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia type 73, is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically has a material basis in a mutation in the CPT1C gene located on chromosome 19q13, defining it as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 74 (HSP74), also known exactly as SPG74 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 74, is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is a specific condition that fundamentally stems from autosomal recessive inheritance. HSP74 is defined by a mutation in the IBA57 gene located on chromosome 1q42.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 75 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this hereditary spastic paraplegia, identified as SPG75, also known as autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 75 or autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 75, is defined by a mutation in the MAG gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 76 (HSP76) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of hereditary spastic paraplegia. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of HSP76 is a hereditary spastic paraplegia that arises from a mutation in the CAPN1 gene located on chromosome 11q13. HSP76 is also exactly referred to as SPG76 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 76.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 77 (HSP77) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease, which means it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific condition is defined by a hereditary spastic paraplegia that has its material basis in a mutation in the FARS2 gene located on chromosome 6p25. It is also exactly synonymous with SPG77 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 77, highlighting its genetic basis and classification within hereditary spastic paraplegias.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 8 (HSP8) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is specifically characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and has a definition centered around a mutation in the KIAA0196 gene located on chromosome 8q24. HSP8 is also known by the exact synonyms SPG8, autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 8, and autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia type 8.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 9a is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, which falls under the broader category of hereditary spastic paraplegia. This particular condition is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, hereditary spastic paraplegia 9a is defined by a hereditary spastic paraplegia that results from an autosomal dominant heterozygous mutation in the ALDH18A1 gene located on chromosome 10q24. It is known by several exact synonyms, including AD-SPG9A, Cataracts motor neuropathy-short stature-skeletal anomalies syndrome, SPG9A, autosomal dominant complex spastic paraplegia type 9A, autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 9A, cataracts with motor neuronopathy, short stature and skeletal abnormalities, spastic paraparesis with amyopathy, cataracts and gastroesophageal reflux, and spastic paraparesis-amyopathy-cataracts-gastroesophageal reflux syndrome.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 9b (SPG9B) is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and an autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia that has its material basis in autosomal recessive homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ALDH18A1 gene on chromosome 10q24. Furthermore, hereditary spastic paraplegia 9b is also known by its exact synonyms: autosomal recessive complex spastic paraplegia type 9B and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 9B.

Usher syndrome type 1 is a type of Usher syndrome characterized by profound congenital deafness, vestibular dysfunction, and early development of retinitis pigmentosa. It has exact synonyms US1 and USH1.

Usher Syndrome Type 2 is a type of Usher Syndrome characterized by mild to severe congenital hearing impairment, normal vestibular function, and the later development of retinitis pigmentosa. It also has the exact synonym USH2.

Usher syndrome type 3 is a specific type of Usher syndrome characterized by progressive hearing loss that typically begins in late childhood, variable vestibular dysfunction, and the onset of retinitis pigmentosa by the second decade of life. It also has the exact synonym USH3.

Retinitis pigmentosa deafness syndrome is a type of Usher syndrome and also a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by retinitis pigmentosa and the onset of sensorineural hearing impairment in the teens, with its material basis in a mutation in the MTTS2 gene in the mitochondrial genome. Additionally, this syndrome is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Usher syndrome type 1C, which has exact synonyms such as USH1C, Usher syndrome type I Acadian variety, and Usher syndrome type IC, is a subtype of Usher syndrome type 1. This particular type is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Usher syndrome type 1C is defined by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the USH1C gene on chromosome 11p15.

Usher syndrome type 1D is a type of digenic disease, which is specifically a form of Usher syndrome type 1. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and digenic inheritance. It is defined as an Usher syndrome type 1 that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDH23 gene on chromosome 10q22. Additionally, Usher syndrome type 1D is exactly synonymous with USH1D and Usher syndrome type ID.

Usher syndrome type 1F is a subtype of Usher syndrome type 1 and also falls under categories that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific syndrome, Usher syndrome type 1F, is defined as an Usher syndrome type 1 that occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PCDH15 gene located on chromosome 10q. Furthermore, Usher syndrome type 1F is precisely synonymous with USH1F and Usher syndrome type IF.

Usher syndrome type 1E is a type of Usher syndrome type 1, and it is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 21q21. Furthermore, Usher syndrome type 1E is exactly synonymous with USH1E and Usher syndrome type IE.

Usher syndrome type 1G is a specific type of Usher syndrome type 1 and is also categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an Usher syndrome type 1 that is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the USH1G gene on chromosome 17q25. Furthermore, Usher syndrome type 1G is exactly synonymous with USH1G and Usher syndrome type IG.

Usher syndrome type 1H is a type of Usher syndrome type 1 and is defined as an Usher syndrome type 1 that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 15q22-q23. It is exactly synonymized with USH1H and Usher syndrome type IH.

Usher syndrome type 1J is a subtype of Usher syndrome type 1, and it is classified as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as an Usher syndrome type 1 that is caused by a homozygous mutation in the CIB2 gene located on chromosome 15q24. It is also referred to by the exact synonyms USH1J and Usher syndrome type IJ.

Usher syndrome type 1K is a subtype of Usher syndrome type 1, and it is also categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular type, Usher syndrome type 1K, is defined by a variation in the chromosome region 10p11.21-q21.1. Additionally, it is precisely synonymous with USH1K and Usher syndrome type IK.

Usher Syndrome Type 2A is a subtype of Usher Syndrome Type 2 and is also known as USH2A or Usher Syndrome Type IIA. It is defined as an Usher syndrome type 2 characterized by moderate to severe sensorineural hearing loss, which mainly affects the perception of high-frequency sounds, and progressive retinitis pigmentosa. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the USH2A gene on chromosome 1q41. Moreover, Usher Syndrome Type 2A is a condition that requires autosomal recessive inheritance for its manifestation.

Usher syndrome type 2C (USH2C) is a type of digenic disease, which is a specific category of Usher syndrome type 2. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance as well as digenic inheritance. This particular syndrome is defined by an Usher syndrome type 2 that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ADGRV1 gene located on chromosome 5q14. Additionally, Usher syndrome type 2C is precisely referred to by exact synonyms such as USH2C, Usher syndrome IIC, and Usher syndrome type IIC.

Usher syndrome type 2D is a specific type of Usher syndrome type 2 and is also known as USH2D or Usher syndrome type IID. This condition arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WHRN gene located on chromosome 9q32 and is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Usher syndrome type 3A is a subtype of Usher syndrome type 3 and is also a type of condition that necessarily involves autosomal recessive inheritance. It is distinctly separate from Usher syndrome type 3B. The definition of Usher syndrome type 3A specifies that it is an Usher syndrome type 3 characterized by having its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CLRN1 gene located on chromosome 3q25. Furthermore, Usher syndrome type 3A is precisely referred to by the exact synonyms USH3A and Usher syndrome type IIIA.

Usher syndrome type 3B is a subtype of Usher syndrome type 3 and is categorized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an Usher syndrome type 3 that arises from a homozygous mutation in the HARS gene located on chromosome 5q31. Furthermore, Usher syndrome type 3B is exactly synonymous with USH3B and Usher syndrome type IIIB.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group A is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by the involvement of the central and peripheral nervous systems in addition to cutaneous lesions. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the XPA gene on chromosome 9q22. It has several exact synonyms, including XP group A, XP1, XPA, xeroderma pigmentosum 1, and xeroderma pigmentosum complementation group A.

Xeroderma Pigmentosum Group C is a type of Xeroderma Pigmentosum characterized by an increased propensity to develop malignant melanoma that has its material basis in a mutation in the XPC gene on chromosome 3p25. It has exact synonyms including XP Group C, XP3, XPC, XPCC, and Xeroderma Pigmentosum III.

    :has_definition "A xeroderma pigmentosum that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the excision repair gene ERCC2 on chromosome 19q13." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "XP group D"@en,
        "XP group H"@en,
        "XP4"@en,
        "XP8"@en,
        "XPD"@en,
        "XPDC"@en,

text: Xeroderma pigmentosum group D is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by a xeroderma pigmentosum that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the excision repair gene ERCC2 on chromosome 19q13. It is exactly synonymous with XP group D, XP group H, XP4, XP8, XPD, XPDC, XPH, xeroderma pigmentosum IV, and xeroderma pigmentosum VIII.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group E is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by a mild phenotype that results from a homozygous mutation in the DDB2 gene located on chromosome 11p11. It is exactly synonymous with XP group E, XP5, XPE, and xeroderma pigmentosum V.

Xeroderma pigmentosum variant type is a subtype of xeroderma pigmentosum, characterized by normal DNA excision repair, but defective postreplication repair due to mutations in the POLH gene on chromosome 6p21.1. It is exactly synonymous with XPV, photosensitivity with defective DNA synthesis, and xeroderma pigmentosum with normal DNA repair rates.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group F is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by milder symptoms and later onset of skin cancer, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC4 gene on chromosome 16p13. Furthermore, xeroderma pigmentosum group F is exactly synonymous with XP group F, XP6, XPF, and xeroderma pigmentosum VI.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group G is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by a xeroderma pigmentosum that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC5 gene on chromosome 13q33. It is exactly synonymous with XP group G, XP7, XPG, and xeroderma pigmentosum VII.

Xeroderma pigmentosum group B is a type of xeroderma pigmentosum characterized by a material basis in mutation in the ERCC3 gene on chromosome 2q14. It is exactly synonymous with XP group B, XPB, and XPBC.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 1 is a type of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata, defined by a condition that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX7 gene on chromosome 6q23.3. It is precisely synonymous with Pbd9, Peroxisome Biogenesis Disorder 9, and Rcdp1.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 2 is a subtype of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata, characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GNPAT gene on chromosome 1q42.2. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Chondrodysplasia Punctata, Rhizomelic, Due To Dihydroxyacetonephosphate Acyltransferase Deficiency, Dhapat Deficiency, Dihydroxyacetonephosphate Acyltransferase Deficiency, Glyceronephosphate O-Acyltransferase Deficiency, Gnpat Deficiency, Peroxisomal Dihydroxyacetonephosphate Acyltransferase Deficiency, and Rcdp2.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 3 is a specific type of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata defined by an autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AGPS gene on chromosome 2q31.2. It is exactly synonymous with Agps Deficiency, Alkyldihydroxyacetonephosphate Synthase Deficiency, Alkylglycerone-Phosphate Synthase Deficiency, and Rcdp3.

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 5, also known exactly as Rcdp5, is a type of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata. It is defined as a rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX5 gene on chromosome 12p13.31.

Posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is a posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy that arises due to an autosomal dominant inheritance of mutation in the OVOL2 gene located on chromosome 20p11.23. This condition is also known by several exact synonyms, including Ched1, Corneal Endothelial Dystrophy 1, Autosomal Dominant, Maumenee Corneal Dystrophy, and Ppcd1.

Posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 2 (PPCD2) is a specific type of posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. PPCD2 is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the COL8A2 gene located on chromosome 1p34.3. Additionally, PPCD2 is also precisely known by its exact synonym, PPCD2.

Posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 3 (PPCD3) is a kind of monogenic disease and a specific type of posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy, indicating it is based on genetic factors. It is defined as a posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ZEB1 gene located on chromosome 10p11.22. Additionally, PPCD3 is exactly synonymous with Ppcd3.

Polycystic kidney disease 1 is a type of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease, which is defined as an autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of mutation in the PKD1 gene on chromosome 16p13.3. Additionally, polycystic kidney disease 1 is exactly synonymous with Apkd1, Pkd1, and Polycystic Kidney Disease, Adult, Type I.

Polycystic kidney disease 2 is a type of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease, defined as an autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease that has its material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the PKD2 gene on chromosome 4q22.1. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with Apkd2, Pkd2, and Polycystic Kidney Disease, Adult, Type II.

Polycystic kidney disease 3 is a type of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease, which is defined as an autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of mutation in the GANAB gene on chromosome 11q12.3. It has exact synonyms: Apkd3, Pkd3, and Polycystic Kidney Disease, Adult, Type III.

Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease (ARPKD) is a type of disease that falls under multiple categories: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a type of polycystic kidney disease, and is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. ARPKD is defined as a polycystic kidney disease characterized by the presence of multiple cysts located in the kidney, which result from ciliopathy that disrupts the function of the primary cilium, and it is inherited in an autosomal recessive fashion. Furthermore, ARPKD is known by several exact synonyms including Arpkd, Pkhd1, Polycystic Kidney Disease, Infantile, Type I, and Polycystic Kidney and Hepatic Disease 1.

Congenital Stationary Night Blindness Autosomal Dominant 1 (CSNBAD1), also known as Rhodopsin-related Congenital Stationary Night Blindness, is a type of congenital stationary night blindness and an autosomal dominant disease. It is classified as a disease that has at least some material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is linked to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This specific condition is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance with a material basis in mutations in the RHO gene on chromosome 3q22.1.

Congenital Stationary Night Blindness Autosomal Dominant 2 (CSNBAD2), also known as Rambusch type congenital stationary night blindness, is a type of congenital stationary night blindness and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The condition specifically has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PDE6B gene located on chromosome 4p16. This defines CSNBAD2 as a disorder that not only aligns with the characteristics of congenital stationary night blindness but also embodies the genetic and developmental aspects of autosomal dominant diseases.

Congenital stationary night blindness 1f (CSNB1F) is a type of congenital stationary night blindness and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is also associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, this condition is defined by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern that has its material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the LRIT3 gene on chromosome 4q25. Furthermore, congenital stationary night blindness 1f is exactly synonymous with CSNB1F and congenital stationary night blindness 1F autosomal recessive.

Congenital Stationary Night Blindness 1B (CSNB1B), which also goes by the exact synonyms Autosomal Recessive Complete Congenital Stationary Night Blindness and Congenital Stationary Night Blindness 1B Autosomal Recessive, is a type of Congenital Stationary Night Blindness and is classified under autosomal recessive diseases. This condition specifically arises due to a mutation in the GRM6 gene located on chromosome 5q35, exemplifying an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. Moreover, it is characterized by abnormalities related to prenatal development or birth, highlighting its foundation in such developmental irregularities.

Congenital stationary night blindness 1h (CSNB1H), also known as congenital stationary night blindness type 1H, is a type of congenital stationary night blindness and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The condition is defined by autosomal recessive inheritance and has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNB3 gene on chromosome 12p13.

Congenital Stationary Night Blindness 1C (CSNB1C) is a type of Congenital Stationary Night Blindness and an autosomal recessive disease. Specifically, it is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is also linked to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. The condition is defined by autosomal recessive inheritance that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRPM1 gene on chromosome 15q13-q14. Additionally, CSNB1C has exact synonyms, including "congenital stationary night blindness 1C autosomal recessive."

Congenital stationary night blindness 1d (CSNB1D) is a type of congenital stationary night blindness and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLC24A1 gene on chromosome 15q22. This condition is also related to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Congenital stationary night blindness 1D autosomal recessive is an exact synonym for CSNB1D.

Congenital stationary night blindness 1e is a type of congenital stationary night blindness, autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance as well as a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GPR179 gene on chromosome 17q12. Furthermore, congenital stationary night blindness 1e has the exact synonyms CSNB1E and congenital stationary night blindness 1E autosomal recessive.

Congenital Stationary Night Blindness 1a (CSNB1A) is a type of congenital stationary night blindness, which is a category of X-linked recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and involves an abnormality of prenatal development or birth. The disease is defined by a mutation in the NYX gene located on chromosome Xp11.4. CSNB1A is also known by several exact synonyms, including CSNB1A, NBMI, complete CSNB X-linked, congenital stationary night blindness 1A X-linked, congenital stationary night blindness with myopia, hemeralopia-myopia, and myopia-night blindness.

Congenital stationary night blindness 2A is a type of congenital stationary night blindness and also a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and involves an abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital stationary night blindness 2A is defined by a mutation in the CACNA1F gene located on chromosome Xp11.23. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with congenital stationary night blindness 2A X-linked.

Holoprosencephaly 2, also known exactly as HPE2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of holoprosencephaly. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this variant of holoprosencephaly, HPE2, is defined as having its material basis in mutations in the homeobox-containing SIX3 gene located on chromosome 2p21.

Holoprosencephaly 9 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of holoprosencephaly, which at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a holoprosencephaly that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GLI2 gene located on chromosome 2q14. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with HPE9, holoprosencephaly with microphthalmia and first branchial arch anomalies, and pituitary anomalies with holoprosencephaly-like features.
Holoprosencephaly 6 is a type of holoprosencephaly and has an exact synonym, HPE6. It is defined as a holoprosencephaly that has a material basis in variation in the chromosome region 2q37.1-q37.3.

Holoprosencephaly 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of holoprosencephaly that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a holoprosencephaly that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SHH gene on chromosome 7q36. Additionally, Holoprosencephaly 3 has exact synonyms, including HLP3 and HPE3.

Holoprosencephaly 7, which is also exactly known as HPE7, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of holoprosencephaly. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this type of holoprosencephaly has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PTCH1 gene located on chromosome 9q22.

Holoprosencephaly 11, which has the exact synonym HPE11, is a type of holoprosencephaly and a specific kind of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a holoprosencephaly that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the CDON gene located on chromosome 11q24.

Holoprosencephaly 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of holoprosencephaly. It is characterized as something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition, also exactly known as HPE5, is defined as a holoprosencephaly that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the ZIC2 gene located on chromosome 13q32.

Holoprosencephaly 8 is a type of holoprosencephaly, which is defined as a holoprosencephaly that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 14q13. It is also exactly synonymous with HPE8.

Holoprosencephaly 4, which has the exact synonym HPE4, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of holoprosencephaly. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined as a holoprosencephaly that results from a heterozygous mutation in the TGIF gene on chromosome 18p11.

Holoprosencephaly 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of holoprosencephaly, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a holoprosencephaly that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 21q22.3. Moreover, Holoprosencephaly 1 has an exact synonym, HPE1.

Inflammatory Bowel Disease 7 (IBD7) is a type of monogenic disease and a specific form of inflammatory bowel disease that is rooted in a genetic basis. It is defined as an inflammatory bowel disease that has its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 1p36. Additionally, it is also exactly synonymous with IBD7.

Inflammatory Bowel Disease 17 (IBD17) is a type of monogenic disease, which means it is a form of disease that has its basis in variations in a single gene. Specifically, it is an inflammatory bowel disease, categorized under conditions that at least have their basis in some gene-related issues. The definition of IBD17 highlights that it is an inflammatory bowel disease that has its material basis in variations in the IL23R gene located on chromosome 1p31.3. Additionally, IBD17 is exactly synonymous with IBD17, indicating that both terms refer to the same condition.

Inflammatory Bowel Disease 23 (IBD23) is a type of monogenic disease, which means it is a type of disease that has its basis in some gene. It falls under the broader category of Inflammatory Bowel Diseases. Specifically, IBD23 is characterized by having its material basis in variation in the chromosome region 1q32.1. Furthermore, IBD23 is also known by its exact synonym, IBD23.
